Important limitations of the script

It is useful, but there are a few methodological caveats:

It checks submitted input symbols against the other list’s synonym space using the original input text, not the resolved approved symbol. That means overlap depends partly on what form of the symbol was originally entered.

GO overlap is very broad: a gene is counted as overlapping if it shares any GO term with any gene in the other list. This is not gene-by-gene orthology and not enrichment analysis.

There is no ortholog mapping between species. Cross-species matches are based on shared names/synonyms and shared GO annotations, not formal ortholog relationships.

Multiple matches for one symbol are collapsed together, which can obscure ambiguity.

GO mappings depend entirely on the quality and completeness of the external annotation files.


Methods section draft

Here is a research-style methods section you can use and adapt:

Gene list harmonization and cross-species comparison

Three species-specific gene lists were analyzed, corresponding to human, cattle, and pig. For each list, gene symbols were supplied as the first column of a comma-separated input file. Input values were trimmed for whitespace, empty entries were removed, and duplicate symbols were collapsed to unique entries prior to downstream processing.

Reference nomenclature resources

Gene nomenclature was standardized using predownloaded reference tables from the HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee (HGNC) for human genes and the Vertebrate Gene Nomenclature Committee (VGNC) for non-human vertebrate genes. From these resources, the approved gene symbol, approved gene name, stable identifier, previous symbols, and alias symbols were extracted. The VGNC table was filtered by taxonomic identifier to retain cattle (taxon ID 9913) and pig (taxon ID 9823) entries.

Gene Ontology annotation mapping

Species-specific Gene Ontology (GO) annotation files were imported from predownloaded tab-delimited files generated from Ensembl BioMart. For each species, the file was required to contain a gene stable identifier and GO accession. When available, GO term names and GO domain assignments were also retained. Stable gene identifiers were normalized by removing version suffixes. GO annotations were then aggregated per gene, generating collapsed fields for all GO IDs, all GO term names, and domain-specific GO identifiers corresponding to biological process, molecular function, and cellular component categories.

Gene symbol normalization and annotation expansion

For each species, a lookup index was constructed from the nomenclature reference table using the approved symbol together with all previous and alias symbols. All lookup terms were normalized by converting to lowercase and trimming whitespace. Each submitted input symbol was queried against this synonym index in a case-insensitive manner. When a match was identified, the corresponding approved symbol, approved gene name, stable identifier, and all associated nomenclature variants were retrieved. GO annotations were then joined to matched genes using the stable gene identifier. If multiple reference entries matched a submitted symbol, the resulting approved symbols, names, identifiers, and GO terms were collapsed into comma-separated fields. Symbols without a reference match were retained in the output and marked as not found in the nomenclature database.

Cross-list comparison

Expanded gene lists were compared pairwise across all three species. Two complementary overlap metrics were calculated.

First, nomenclature-based overlap was assessed by determining whether each original input symbol from one list was present among the normalized set of names associated with genes in a second list, where the searchable name space included approved symbols, previous symbols, and aliases.

Second, functional overlap was assessed using GO annotations. For each gene in one list, overlap was recorded when at least one GO identifier assigned to that gene was also present in the union of GO identifiers observed in a comparison list. This analysis was performed independently for all pairwise list combinations.

Output generation

For each input gene list, an expanded annotation table was exported containing the submitted symbol, species label, approved symbol, approved gene name, stable identifier, concatenated nomenclature variants, database match status, and aggregated GO annotations. Additional pairwise detail tables were generated containing boolean indicators for nomenclature overlap and GO overlap with each of the other two lists. A final summary table reported, for each pairwise comparison direction, the total number of input symbols, the number and percentage of symbols with nomenclature-based overlap, and the number and percentage of symbols with GO-based overlap.

